This is a $0/0$ form. Apply L’Hospital twice:
$$\lim_{x\to 0}\frac{e^x-1-x}{x^2}
=\lim_{x\to 0}\frac{e^x-1}{2x}\quad(0/0)
=\lim_{x\to 0}\frac{e^x}{2}
=\frac{1}{2}.$$
The table in figure 4.7-P2 is consistent with values approaching $0.500000\ldots$.

Rationalize:
$$\frac{\sqrt{1+3x}-1}{x}\cdot\frac{\sqrt{1+3x}+1}{\sqrt{1+3x}+1}
=\frac{(1+3x)-1}{x(\sqrt{1+3x}+1)}
=\frac{3}{\sqrt{1+3x}+1}.$$
As $x\to 0$, this approaches $\frac{3}{2}$.

Rationalize:
$$\frac{\sqrt{9+h}-3}{h}\cdot\frac{\sqrt{9+h}+3}{\sqrt{9+h}+3}
=\frac{(9+h)-9}{h(\sqrt{9+h}+3)}
=\frac{1}{\sqrt{9+h}+3}.$$
Then
$$\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{1}{\sqrt{9+h}+3}=\frac{1}{3+3}=\frac{1}{6}.$$

This is a $0/0$ form. Apply L’Hospital:
$$\lim_{x\to 0}\frac{\ln(1+5x)}{x}
=\lim_{x\to 0}\frac{\frac{5}{1+5x}}{1}
=5.$$

Compute the difference quotient:
$$\frac{f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}=\frac{\frac{1}{a+h}-\frac{1}{a}}{h}
=\frac{\frac{a-(a+h)}{a(a+h)}}{h}
=\frac{\frac{-h}{a(a+h)}}{h}
=-\frac{1}{a(a+h)}.$$

This is a $0/0$ form. Apply L’Hospital three times:
$$\lim_{x\to 0}\frac{\sin x-x}{x^3}
=\lim_{x\to 0}\frac{\cos x-1}{3x^2}
=\lim_{x\to 0}\frac{-\sin x}{6x}
=\lim_{x\to 0}\frac{-\cos x}{6}
=-\frac{1}{6}.$$
